The '''Australian Freedom League''' (AFL) was an anti-[[conscription]] organisation founded in Australia in 1912.  Growing out of an earlier organisation called the "Anti-Military Service League",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Summy|first1=Hilary N.|title='Peace Angel' of World War I|date=2006|publisher=University of Queensland|location=Brisbane|isbn=0977506207}}</ref> it was initially based in [[Adelaide]], although by 1914 there were branches in every state except [[Western Australia]].  It was active in producing pamphlets and other material to promote its views that military training would have a negative and corrupting effect on young men and boys.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hamel-Green|first1=Michael|title=Early opposition to the 1911 “Boy Conscription” Scheme|url=http://livingpeacemuseum.org.au/ALPM/exhibits/show/ww1/ww1-opposition-conscription|website=Australian Living Peace Museum|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>

